<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> DiTomaso and Healy (2007) consider six species of broom and gorse as major weeds in California. These long-lived legumes have showy, yellow flowers, and they produce abundant seed that collect in long-lived seed banks. Plants sprout from their rootstocks after cutting and fire (Alvarez 2000, Bossard 2000a, Hoshovsky 2000b, Nilsen 2000). The first four brooms listed are the most conspicuous of the 12 broom species naturalizing in the state. Many forms exist in the horticultural trade. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Cytisus scoparius, </i>Scotch broom, has a Cal-IPC rank of High and a CDFA list of C. It has 5-angled stems, few leaves, and bright yellow to maroon flowers. Stands occur throughout northern cismontane California. The typical variety with yellow flowers (var. <i>scoparius</i>) is joined along the Northern California Coast (263A) with var. <i>andreanus, </i>with brownish-red wing petals and yellow standard (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Cytisus striatus, </i>Portuguese broom, has a Cal-IPC rank of Moderate. It is easily confused with <i>C. scoparius, </i>but the stems of this broom are 8- to 10-angled, and the calyx is pubescent. It grows in the San Francisco Bay area (261Ac), Southern California Coast (261B) and Peninsular Ranges (M262Bb). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Genista monspessulana, </i>French broom, has a Cal-IPC rank of High and a CDFA list of C. It has 8-10-ridged stems, leafy branches, and small clusters of yellow flowers. Stands occur throughout cismontane California. Many stands on the Central California Coast (261A) are hybrids with <i>G. canariensis </i>or <i>G. stenopetala </i>(DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Retama monosperma, </i>Bridal broom, has a Cal-IPC rank of Moderate alert. It has white flowers and drooping branches (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). Botanical literature also uses the name <i>Genista monosperma</i>. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Spartium junceum, </i>Spanish broom, has a Cal-IPC rank of High and a CDFA list of C. It has round, fine-ridged stems; ephemeral, simple leaves; and large yellow flowers. It is the most drought resistant of the brooms and establishes throughout cismontane California in areas with full sun, limited water, and infertile soils (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ulex europaeus, </i>gorse, has a Cal-IPC rank of High and a CDFA list of B. It has stout, thorny branches and yellow flowers. The mature, modified leaves are stiff spines. Stands are mainly in northern parts of cismontane California (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
Other naturalized broom species in California have more localized ranges. <i>Chamaecytisus prolifera </i>is local in the San Francisco Bay area (261Ad, Al). <i>Cytisus multiflorus </i>grows along the Central Coast. <i>Genista canariensis </i>occurs on the Central Coast and in southern California (261B, M262B). <i>G. linifolia </i>exists in Humboldt Co. (263Ae) and southern California. <i>G. maderensis </i>and <i>G. stenopetala </i>are found on the Central Coast (Hickman 1993). <br/>
<br/>
Especially <i>Cytisus scoparius, G. monspessulana, </i>and <i>U. europaeus </i>frequently invade disturbed areas and grasslands along the North Coast (Alexander and D’Antonio 2003, D’Antonio et al. 2007, Keeley 2006). Fire promotes broom invasions because a flush of germination results in grassland and forest openings adjacent to broom patches (Odion and Haubensak 2002). However, broom invasions occur in coastal grasslands even without fire (Tyler et al. 2007).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Cotoneaster </i>species including <i>C. franchetii, C. lacteus, </i>and <i>C. pannosa </i>have a Cal-IPC rank of Moderate alert. Similar to broom species, they have invaded along the California coast due their wide tolerance of environmental conditions and high reproductive success. The leaves of <i>Cotoneaster </i>can be variable, with shaded leaves reaching a larger size than leaves exposed to full sun. Their white to pink flower clusters produce orange to red fruits, in which each plant can produce thousands of fruits every year (Cal-IPC 2021). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Cistus </i>species, or rockrose, are evergreens with profuse and attractive white or pink blooms, including <i>C. incanus </i>and <i>C. ladanifer </i>. These species are cultivated and highly appreciated as ornamentals, originally being brought to Southern California from the Mediterranean in the 1950s. They have a unique resistance to adverse weather conditions and are particularly drought tolerant, allowing them to thrive in California.<br/>
<br/>
This alliance has been expanded since 2009 to include other non-native, primarily Mediterranean scrub species including <i>Cistus, Cotoneaster</i>, and <i>Erica </i>spp. as well as <i>Hypericum canariense</i> which can form dense stands. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
