<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Although brooms are usually top-killed with fire, they sprout from stems, and seeds easily germinate with high seedling densities (Zouhar 2005a, 2005b). Mature plants of brooms and gorse form dense patches that pose a fire hazard, and burning scarifies seed for active germination (Bossard 2000a, Hoshovsky 2000b, Nilsen 2000, Zouhar 2005a, 2005b). They change the soil conditions and increase fire frequency and intensity. However, high-severity fires and repeat fires in some seasons may kill and prevent post-fire sprouting of brooms, so fire may be an effective management tool in certain situations (Zouhar 2005b).</div>
