    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac, Ah-j). <i>Genista monspessulana </i>forms stands in the East Bay Hills, often adjacent to <i>Eucalyptus </i>plantings or those of <i>Pinus radiata</i>. <i>G. monspessulana </i>invades disturbed areas in maritime chaparral stands from San Mateo Co. on around to the Monterey Bay, where several rare native species grow (Van Dyke et al. 2001). Stands of <i>Ulex europaeus </i>infest open space north of Mount San Bruno State Park, and at least two stands of <i>Hypericum canariense </i>occur as dense patches as well in San Mateo Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-c, Af, Ai). Probable stands based on multiple CCH and Calflora records of both <i>Genista monspessulana </i>and  <i>Cytisus scoparius</i>, including records with high numbers of plants or percent cover (Consortium of California Herbaria 2018; Calflora 2021).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). Stands of <i>Genista monspessulana </i>mapped at Point Reyes and Golden Gate National Recreation Area (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a) and at Marin Municipal Watershed lands (Evens and Kentner 2006) have had active removal programs for over ten years. Stands of other non-native Mediterranean scrub including <i>Cytisus scoparius, Cistus, </i> and <i>Cotoneaster, </i>spp. also occur in Marin Co. (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021). Associated species include <i>Baccharis pilularis, Ceanothus thyrsiflorus, </i>and <i>Toxicodendron diversilobum. </i>Dense <i>G. monspessulana </i>stands also occur in other areas of Marin Co. (Alexander and D’Antonio 2003), including China Camp State Park (Parker and Haubensak 2002), with a variety of other invasive plants. <i>Ulex europaea </i>and <i>G. monspessulana </i>are common along the coast and often invade coastal grasslands in Sonoma and Mendocino Cos.; <i>Erica lusitanica, G. monspessulana </i>and <i>Cytisus scoparius </i>form dense stands along roadways adjacent to redwood forests in Humboldt Co. (Sawyer et al. 2000b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ed, Ef-g). Probable stands based on multiple CCH and Calflora records of both <i>Genista monspessulana </i>and  <i>Cytisus scoparius</i>, including records with high numbers of plants or percent cover (Consortium of California Herbaria 2018; Calflora 2021).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fb). Stands of <i>G. monspessulana </i>occur along roadsides in the northern foothills.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands of <i>Spartium junceum </i>in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) contain coastal scrub species and emergent <i>Quercus agrifolia </i>trees. <i>Retama monosperma </i>is quickly spreading in San Diego Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bg, Bn-o). Stands of <i>Spartium junceum, </i>planted in road cuts, are spreading in the San Bernardino Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Dm). Probable stands based on multiple CCH and Calflora records of both <i>Genista monspessulana </i>and  <i>Cytisus scoparius</i>, including records with high numbers of plants or percent cover (Consortium of California Herbaria 2018; Calflora 2021).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> All these shrubs displace natives and make restoration difficult. Methods of removal and control are discussed by various researchers (DiTomaso and Healy 2007, Haubensak and D’Antonio 2006, Hoshovsky 2000b, Nilsen 2000, Zouhar 2005a, 2005b, 2005d). Brooms are nitrogen fixers and enhance soil nitrogen levels (Haubensak et al. 2004). They can alter soil conditions that initially support this non-native shrubland, and invasions may favor other non-natives, including exotic herbs, even when these shrubs are removed or die (Haubensak et al. 2004). Seed banks develop with stand establishment, requiring a long-term commitment for effective eradication (J. Klein pers. Comm. 2005). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Associations</h4>
        
            
